<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>How to Use This Calculator</h2>

  <h3>Taxable income</h3>
  <p>Enter your <strong>taxable income</strong> — that's your gross income minus deductions (standard or itemized). The calculator breaks it down across all federal brackets so you can see exactly how much falls into each rate.</p>

  <h3>Filing status</h3>
  <p>Select your <strong>filing status</strong> to apply the correct bracket thresholds. Married Filing Jointly brackets are roughly double the Single brackets, which can significantly lower your marginal rate.</p>

  <h3>Visual bracket breakdown</h3>
  <p>The calculator shows a <strong>visual breakdown</strong> of how your income is split across brackets — making it easy to see where most of your tax comes from and where you land on the marginal rate scale.</p>

  <h3>Share your result</h3>
  <p>Every input is encoded in the URL. Click <strong>Share</strong>, send the link — they'll see your exact numbers. No re-entering, no screenshots.</p>
</section>

<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>The US federal income tax uses <strong>progressive brackets</strong>. Each range of income is taxed at its own rate — you don't pay your top marginal rate on all income, only on the portion that falls within that bracket.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Federal Tax = &sum; (Income in Each Bracket &times; Bracket Rate)<br><br>
    Effective Rate = Total Tax &divide; Taxable Income &times; 100%
  </div>

  <h3>2025 Federal Tax Brackets — Single</h3>
  <div class="example-data">
    <div class="example-row"><span class="label">10%</span><span class="value">$0 – $11,925</span></div>
    <div class="example-row"><span class="label">12%</span><span class="value">$11,926 – $48,475</span></div>
